Wherefor Rt Thou.

Hello! Welcome to Week 2: The week that we sink our teeth into some R programming basics. Non-coincidentally, its also the week that youll start feeling (and feeding) embers of rage and exasperation that were previously lying unacknowledged in the depths of your psyche

In all seriousness, R is just like any other language in that it takes consistent practice to summit the learning curve.

So lets jump into it!

Challenge 1: R Code

Arguably, the most important part of learning R Markdown is learning how to share and visualize your R code. So, your first challenge. Make a code chunk where you:

  • Install the tidyverse package

  • Use library() to bring the tidyverse package into the current session.

  • Set up your working directory

  • Make a character string containing your 3 favorite bands. Assign it to an appropriately named variable.

  • Make a function that looks to see if a number is even. Make your function tell the user whether it is or isnt.

  • Call the function with any number you choose.

divisible_by_13(169)
## [1] "Don't show this number to someone suffering from triskaidekaphobia"
divisible_by_13(666)
## [1] "Jason Vorhees is sad."
Bonus: Make a vector of all the numbers between 1-1000 without writing them all out

Challenge 2: Prettify your text.

The other core idea for R Markdown is to, you know, write stuff. Writing is one of humanitys oldest technologies. It is also, in my opinion, its most magical:

This sentence has five words. Here are five more words. Five word sentences are fine. But several together become monotonous. Listen to what is happening. The writing is getting boring. The sound of it drones. Its like a stuck record. The ear demands some variety."

Now listen. I vary sentence length, and I create music. Music. I use short sentences. And I use sentences of medium length. And sometimes when I am certain the reader is rested, I will engage them with a sentence of considerable length, a sentence that burns with energy and builds with all the impetus of a crescendo, the roll of the drums, the crash of the cymbalssounds that say listen to this, it is important.

So write with a combination of short, medium, and long setnences. Create a sound that pleases the readers ear. Dont just write words. Write music.

Adapted from Gary Provost

This isnt English class; Im not going to judge you on the quality or sonorousness of your prose. However, there are simple tricks to make anyones text more engagingand thats with the judicious use of formating. So, for the next challenge: Write me a paragraph. It doesnt have to be long; Im not going to count periods and dock you because according to the standards of the FCAT/FSA/FTS, a paragraph is technically at least three complete sentences and yadda yadda yadda. Go nuts. Write about anything you want. Just make sure that youve shown that you know how to do the following:

  • Bold words.

  • Italicize words

  • Bold & Italicize words

  • Use an em dash like this.

  • Use an en dash, as if you were talking about a scale from 0100.

  • Strike through your text.

  • Add a hyperlink

Bonus: Add emojis

Challenge 3: Show Me the Data

In general, you want to be as visible and open with your data as possible. Its not only good scientific practice, but its tremendously helpful for catching errors. The one of the ironclad laws of the internet is if you post something thats erroneous, someone is bound to appear to tell you what you did wrong. And while this is often something we dread in our day-to-day livesas scientists, its tremendously helpful! If were in the pursuit of Truth (or at least reliably actionable information), then being corrected is a good thing! (Although many correcters could learn to be a bit less stuck-up about it)

So show off your data! Or at least a few rows of it. In this case, show me a preview of the in-built mtcars dataset.

mpg cyl disp hp drat wt qsec vs am gear carb
Mazda RX4 21.0 6 160 110 3.90 2.620 16.46 0 1 4 4
Mazda RX4 Wag 21.0 6 160 110 3.90 2.875 17.02 0 1 4 4
Datsun 710 22.8 4 108 93 3.85 2.320 18.61 1 1 4 1
Hornet 4 Drive 21.4 6 258 110 3.08 3.215 19.44 1 0 3 1
Hornet Sportabout 18.7 8 360 175 3.15 3.440 17.02 0 0 3 2
Valiant 18.1 6 225 105 2.76 3.460 20.22 1 0 3 1
Bonus: Make it a pretty table like this rather than just the default R output.

Challenge 4: Just the Facts, Maam. (Or at least the chart).

I know I just said that you want to be as open as possibleand thats true!but sometimes you dont want to show off everything thats going on under the hood. Sometimes youre working with data or a package thats proprietary. Sometimes youre showing off a model with output code that runs forever and you really just want to show the set up. Sometimes (read: often) youre presenting to an audience that couldnt give a flip less about the code but want to see the results. Sometimes it just gets in the way of communicating the story youre trying to present with the data. For example, the function divide_by_13 I used in Challenge 1 isnt in base R. I made the function in a hidden code chunk just before I ran it publicly. Why didnt I show it? Because it would have deleteriously affected the flow of information. (And, also, yall wouldve been able to just change 2 characters to get the correct answer and that kinda defeats the whole purpose of a challenge, right?).

So I want you to do two things using the code from the first figure in section 3.2.2 in R for Data Science.

  1. Make a chunk where the code is visualized but isnt evaluated. Like this:
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
  1. Make a chunk where the code is evaluated but isnt visible. Like this:

Challenge 6: Make your Github site.

Last week, you installed GitHub and reserved space for your blog. Right now, though, if you went to the site, youll probably just get a lonely little hello world among a barren sea of white internet space. Today, were going to make that space into an actual, functional blog that youll use for your assignments. (And, hopefully, to write about all the cool election science stuff youll be doing once youre done with this class.)

If youre having difficulty getting the blog set-up before next class, be sure to come to office hours ASAP or email me for an appointment.

Go to this site to the free online version of blogdown: Creating Websites with R Markdown by Xie, Thomas, and Presmanes Hill. From this weeks reading assignment, you should have some familiarity with Chapters 1 & 2. Now go back and follow the workflow suggested in 1.7, using either the themes suggested in 1.6 or from themes.gohugo.io, and make your blog. You can refer to the instructions in Chapter 1.2 and the information in Chapter 2 to help you out if you get a bit stuck. I also recommend using Making a Website Using Blogdown, Hugo, and Github Pages as a helpful reference as its really accessible and was written by one of the books authors, Amber Thomas. However. After youve built the public directory, do not worry about going to netlify.com. Instead, go to GitHub Desktop on your computer and go to the repository that has *USERNAME*.github.io. Then click on the button that says Show in Explorer. It should just have the index file that you made last time.

From there, delete the index file. Go to where youve saved the public directory. Open it up. You should see folders with names like posts page and archives (although your specific file structure will vary a bit based upon the theme youve chosen.) Select all of the items inside the public folder and copy it to your now empty GitHub desktop repository.

From there, return to GitHub Desktop. Click on the blue Commit to master button and then click the button that says push origin on the top right. Give it a few minutes to load and render (like 35) and then go to your github site. You should now see your very own blog that you generated in R! For your assignments, youll use blogdown and RMarkdown to author your own posts! Youre now well on your way to being a public-facing election data scientist.

If you have any troubles with these stepsespecially the last onebe sure to reach out to me via email. Otherwise, have a safe rest of your week and Ill see you next Tuesday.
